### Description

When writing code snippets in Markdown using syntax highlighting of certain languages (in my case, Objective-C), entering an asterisk character causes the rest of the text in the editor window to appear italicized.

[Here](http://i.imgur.com/pQ0eiXh.png) is a screenshot showing the effect of this bug.

[Here](http://i.imgur.com/TXIdJHI.png) is a screenshot showing the same Markdown file's preview. Notice that the text following the code snippet is not italicized.
### Steps to Reproduce

Write a Markdown code snippet in Objective-C. For example:

``` objective-c
- (void)viewDidLoad
{
    [super viewDidLoad];
    SKView *spriteView = (SKView *) self.view;
    spriteView.showsDrawCount = YES;
    spriteView.showsNodeCount = YES;
    spriteView.showsFPS = YES;
}

// In the editor window, this text will appear to be italicized.
```

In the editor window, you will see that the first asterisk in the line `SKView *spriteView = (SKView *) self.view;` causes the rest of the code to appear as if it were being italicized (it is not).

**Expected behavior:** the asterisk within the code snippet is treated as a part of the code and ignored as a Markdown formatting character.

**Actual behavior:** the asterisk within the code snippet is treated as a Markdown formatting character and, as a result, the following text is highlighted to signify that it is being italicized (it is not).
### Versions

atom version 1.5.4
apm version 1.6.0
running on OS X 10.11.3
